Latin America in the fight against the Coronavirus
SÃO PAULO/SANTIAGO/BOGOTÁ/MEXICO CITY – The COVID-19 pandemic is a shock of unprecedented magnitude and unknown duration.
The consequences are already catastrophic.
If we do not confront the crisis resolutely, it could become the most tragic episode in Latin American history.
So far, the political responses in our region have been very different.
Some governments reacted quickly and declared the protection of public health their top priority.
On the other hand, others unfortunately downplayed the dangers of the pandemic, gave their citizens false information, and ignored not only scientific research but also the advice of their own experts.
These leaders chose amidst the tragedy a populist and divisive politics.
Latin America's top priority must be to keep the number of deaths as low as possible.
Politicians must focus on improving healthcare systems, equipping hospitals with resources, temporarily using vacant infrastructure such as hotels or conference centers, and significantly increasing testing capacity.
Moreover, Latin American countries must reject export controls on medical supplies and other vital resources and advocate for additional resources for the World Health Organization (WHO) - in stark contrast to U.S. President Donald Trump and his reckless decision to freeze approximately 500 million dollars in contributions to the WHO.
We need stronger global cooperation among health authorities to increase testing capacity, treat and isolate patients, and develop treatment options and vaccines - in order to finally end the pandemic.
The economic shock is enormous: Not only has the Latin American domestic production been disrupted, but the countries there are also suffering from declining export volumes and prices, income losses due to the lack of tourism and fewer foreign remittances, as well as strong capital outflows.
The supply shock in large parts of the economy could, together with the decline in demand, trigger a contraction spiral.
To prevent this, bold measures are required to protect household incomes.
This means transferring benefits to the victims of the crisis, including informal and independent workers who have no access to employment subsidies or unemployment insurance.
Relief measures for businesses are also important.
Subsidies that help companies pay their wages and social benefits protect both them and their employees during the crisis. Therefore, they are of crucial importance for a rapid economic recovery after the pandemic.
If the wave of bankruptcies is not prevented, the next victims of the pandemic could be the banks.
And at this point, the payment system—and with it the entire economy—is at risk.
Many companies, especially small and medium-sized ones, will suffer significant income losses during the crisis.
Without support, the lack of liquidity will soon turn into a solvency problem.
Tax deferrals, payment delays, and subsidized loans will not be enough.
This crisis requires not only unprecedented credit guarantees from governments to ensure that banks continue to lend money, but also temporary regulatory changes to promote credit expansion.
Even well-capitalized and managed state banks can play a leading role in this.
Generally speaking, while the measures will vary from country to country, extraordinary fiscal resources will probably be required everywhere to accelerate the recovery.
Governments must stimulate employment and economic activity without exacerbating health risks.
The problem is that the fiscal space in Latin America is even narrower today than it was after the global financial crisis of 2008.
Also, fiscal burdens must be offset through budget adjustments in areas of lower priority.
There is, however, a risk of a downgrading of creditworthiness, which can be mitigated by the governments' commitment to correct the higher fiscal deficits within a reasonable timeframe.
However, external support for households and balance sheets is urgently needed – particularly for the smaller and less developed Latin American countries.
If both private companies and states incur higher deficits, the countries' balance of payments are likely to deteriorate as well.
The recent capital outflows from emerging markets – one of the largest reversals in the modern history of financial markets – exacerbate the problem further.
The resulting currency devaluations can have a destabilizing effect.
In many of the region's economies, the only way to cope with these mutually reinforcing shocks will be to obtain much more external support.
Here, the International Monetary Fund (IMF) plays a crucial role.
It must address the short-term currency and fiscal needs of the countries and continue to support the economies in this crisis, the duration of which is highly uncertain.
To do so, it needs more resources and the ability to disburse them quickly.
Latin American governments should jointly call for a revival of the IMF's global reserve currency – special drawing rights, which should reach a volume of one trillion SDR.
Although SDRs are allocated to member countries according to their IMF quotas, a disproportionate distribution could be achieved by establishing a common pool under the Fund's supervision.
In addition, the IMF could create the necessary capacity by immediately doubling the volume of the New Arrangements to Borrow, in order to meet the impending strong demand for credit.
And finally, the Fund must improve access to low-threshold tools with rapid disbursement – such as its Rapid Financing Instrument – or establish new credit facilities for the pandemic, as traditional IMF credit programs cannot be approved in a timely manner.
Large central banks that issue reserve currencies can help by expanding access to currency swaps—either directly or indirectly through the IMF or the Bank for International Settlements, which can channel liquidity to central banks.
Domestically, central banks must use all instruments available to them and create new ones if necessary to supply the financial markets and the economy with sufficient liquidity.
And finally, multilateral development banks (MDBs) such as the World Bank, the Inter-American Development Bank, and the Latin American CAF Development Bank must double the volume of net credit disbursement in the region and tap into highly liquid global capital markets in order to provide further fiscal support.
In exceptional circumstances and in countries without market access, official credit disbursement could be supplemented by a debt relief.
The MDBs should also provide the countries with guidelines on the different policy areas involved in crisis management, including their own estimates of COVID-19 infection and mortality rates – particularly for countries where governments downplay the health threat.
Time plays a decisive role.
This pandemic presents a challenge without precedent in recent history.
The world and the Latin American and Caribbean region cannot afford delayed or inadequate responses.
Mutual trust, transparency, and reason remain the best guidelines in these uncertain times – and not populism or demagogy.
The crisis must not serve as an excuse to weaken our hard-earned civil rights.
Instead, it can serve as an opportunity to strengthen democracy in Latin America and to demonstrate what it can offer to the citizens.
